AU  - Tesar, Linda L.
T1  - The Value of Control in Emerging Markets
PY  - 2010
Y1  - 2010/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhp090
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 23
IS  - 4
SP  - 1741
EP  - 1770
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - When a developed-country multinational firm acquires majority control of a firm in an emerging market, there is an economically large and statistically significant increase in the acquiring firm's stock price. In 1986–2006, developed-market acquirers experienced positive and significant abnormal returns of 1.16%, on average, over a three-day event window. Positive acquirer returns and dollar value gains appear unique to emerging-market mergers and acquisitions and are not replicated when the same developed-market acquirers take over firms in developed markets. The size of the stock price increase is more pronounced (a) the weaker the contracting environment in the emerging market and (b) for industries with high asset intangibility.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhp090
ER  - 



